data.title: Disney History 101
data.text:
“The Sikorsky 61-L Copter Liner”

By 1960, those piston-powered S-55s were still in use by Los Angeles Airways. However, a new Sikorsky production prototype was tested on December 6, 1960 that would revolutionize travel. These new luxurious Sikorskys were designed from the start specifically for airline use and to airline standards - capable of carrying 3 crew members, 28 passengers, and 1000 pounds of cargo. Each one had a General Electric turbine-powered, twin-engine, advertised as “quiet, comfortable, safe!” In April, 1961. the 200-hour tie-down test was completed within 20 days. A provisional Type Certificate was awarded on May 22, 19st, and on June 21 the Type Inspection Authorization was received, with the Final F.A.A. Certificate to follow.

Los Angeles Airways president C.M. Belinn was optimistic about these new helicopters, and expected a growth of “one thousand per cent the first full year of operation and 2000% by the end of the second year.” Five brand new Sikorsky 61-L turbocopters boasting “twin-turbine reliability…all weather flight capability” were expected to be in use by Los Angeles Airways during late 1961. Starting in November of 1961, the first of four S-61L Sikorskys were delivered to the airline. The following year in March of 1962, the airway began operating the S-61Ls.

By 1961, Los Angeles Airways’ passenger Sikorsky “Copter Liners” had carried more than 2,000,000 passengers over 60,000,000 miles, in a “convenient, relaxed way…over freeway jams.” By this time, Los Angeles Airways was making 60 flights per day from Los Angeles International Airport to Disneyland (at $15 for one round-trip fare), Anaheim - and total one-way time, was an astounding 15 minutes (though some historians claim that there were“22 flights a day” to and from Disneyland! That very same year (of 1961), Disneyland’s decision makers were also so confident in Los Angeles Airways’ Sikorsky fleet, that the Disneyland Hotel was given its own Heliport, which accommodated 2 helicopters at one time. The third copter-liner arrived by May of 1962, and by the end of the month, the three had flown a total of 1,597 hours of airtime. The fourth (and final) helicopter was delivered to the company on July 10, 1962.

The helicopters over Disneyland were so popular that when (in 1960) the Los Angeles Sound Effects Company produced a record of sounds (of popular Southern California attractions, intended for use by filmmakers), the Los Angeles Airways Sikorskys were among the tracks included. You may have heard these very sounds over radio or television broadcasts from 1960 onward! A Sikorsky-style commercial helicopter was even featured on this (c.1966) post-Tencennial Disneyland map (below)!

“The Tragic Flight of Los Angeles Airways 61031”

However, just five years after the aforementioned photograph was taken (and after twelve years of service to Disneyland), something terrible would happen that would end this form of transportation to the happiest place on earth. The demise of Los Angeles Airways flights to Disneyland came when one Sikorsky 61L (registration number N300Y, serial number 61031) was involved in a fatal crash on the evening of August 14th, 1968.

Tragically (and mournfully), eighteen passengers and three crew members lost their lives, while en route to Los Angeles International Airport from Disneyland. Mechanical failure was determined to be the cause of this devastating and horrific crash. The National Transportation Safety Board specifically attributed the incident to “fatigue failure of one rotor blade, which resulted in separation of the blade”. The helicopter could not be controlled and quickly fell from the sky. It is unclear if negligence was involved, if the sensor malfunctioned, or if the stress and failure was undetected and sudden. Whatever the case, countless lives were affected and changed forever by this catastrophic event. From 1951 to 1968, there hadn’t been any notable incidents involving commercial Sikorsky helicopters. However, during 1968 there were two situations resulting in many fatalities (the aforementioned one, and another Sikorski S-61L in Paramount). Both of these Sikorskis were in the service of Los Angeles Airways.

“The End of An Era”

Disneyland Guest Hotel Directories continued to list the telephone extension for Los Angeles Airways up to September of 1970. However, not even Golden West’s “eleventh hour” attempt to acquire Los Angeles Airways could save the helicopter commuter airline from what would happen next. The deal fell through, and would result in the demise of Los Angeles Airways airline operation during 1971. Golden West would only briefly take over helicopter operations for a mere five more months, but it was the end of an era (not only for Los Angeles Airways, but) for helicopter flights to and from Disneyland. By the summer of 1971, Vacationland magazine (published three times yearly by Walt Disney Productions and distributed to more than 1,500 hotels, motels, and leading tourist attractions) had stopped advertising Los Angeles Airways’ “Helicarrier service” among the public transportation alternatives serving Disneyland.

However, this wasn’t the end of Igor Sikorsky’s Sikorsky Aircraft Corporation (which was the world’s first mass-producer of helicopters, since 1942). They would go on to manufacture many aircraft designs, such as its 61-L. This particular model is still utilized for military, industrial, and civilian applications to this very day!

Disneyland opened on July 17th, 1955, but on the eve of Disneyland’s first day of operation, Walt Disney promised that “Disneyland will never be completed. It will continue to grow, to add new things, as long as there is imagination left in the world.” Incidentally (a day prior), on June 16, 1955, Walt Disney’s People and Places released the short film (directed by Ben Sharpsteen) introducing audiences of the world to “Switzerland.” Subsequently, an educational color, short film reel was released for sale to the public (at $12), at a run time of 34 minutes. To quote one catalogue: “these films depict the human family in its infinite variety of habits, effectively emphasizing their human relationships, customs and traditions. You'll learn about the land. These are only a sampling of the fascination you’ll encounter in all of these award-winning subjects.”

Before Disneyland had a Matterhorn, there was Holiday Hill! Since August of 1954, some 350,000 cubic feet of excess dirt (that was accumulated during “excavation” and construction of Disneyland) was piled up to formulate the 20-foot-high Holiday Hill (situated behind the original location of Holidayland. According to one figure published in Disneyland LINE magazine (November 22, 1979), the “earth work” was only “70% complete” by November of 1954.

After Disneyland began its first day of operation, the “mountain” was also known as Snow Hill, and one set of c. 1955 souvenir postcards even featured a painted depiction of snow-capped mountains behind Sleeping Beauty Castle, with the title “The Fairy Castle and Snow Mountain” printed on them. John Hernandez recalled: “I remember that I was pulling weeks for some time on SNOW MOUNTAIN. There was just a great big mound of earth then, with weeds and grass growing on it. It was going to be a recreational area, with a mountain on it, covered with snow. It never worked out and, instead, the Matterhorn was built there.”

Soon, horseless carriage vehicles would occasionally make trips along the road around the newly labeled Lookout Mountain, and guests had a habit of journeying up the incline to achieve a stunning panoramic view of Walt Disney’s magic kingdom.

According to “Disneyland: Inside Story”: “One day, an employee from the Disney Studio was visiting the Park and found Walt sitting on a bench between Fantasyland and Tomorrowland, sort of staring off into space. ‘What are you looking at, Walt?’ she asked. ‘My mountain,’ was the response.“ According to Backstage magazine (published Summer, 1965), “Pete Crimmings and Ron Dominguez remember sitting on top of old Lookout Mountain one day with Walt and Lilly. Walt was telling them that some day he planned to build a big mountain on this spot and the Skyway would run through the middle and there would be some kind of a ride going around and though the mountain. Little did they know that this would be the spot on which the Matterhorn was constructed several years later.”

But for now (during 1956), a construction barrier meant the first of several big changes for Lookout Mountain between Fantasyland and Tomorrowland!

The town was overlooked by tree crested mountaintops leading all the way to the most majestic of the Pennine Alp peaks! In personally researching the local topography, they found that there were higher summits in the range (like Weisshorn). Still, the Matterhorn’s summit ranked one of the tallest in the Alps at “precisely 4,477.54 metres high” according to conclusive recent studies conducted in 1999. Top that off with it’s unique four-faced snow-covered summit (composed mostly of dark-gray gneiss), and it isn’t any wonder why the impressive peak “stood above the rest” from Walt Disney’s vantage. At the time, costars Michael Rennie, James Mac Aurthur, and James Donald also joined the production of Walt Disney’s adaptation of James Ramsey Ullman’s “Banner in the Sky,” which was filmed entirely in Europe. Above, actress Janet Monroe seems to be equally impressed with the alpine scenery!

Walt and company were so impressed with the scene, that Walt decided to bring home a souvenir of the Matterhorn to share with audiences. So he mailed a postcard to WED Enterprsises, Inc. engineer and Art Director Vic Greene, bearing a handwritten message on the reverse side reading, “Vic, build this.” This action was typical of Walt’s contributing role toward Disneyland attractions and best summed in his own words: “Of all the things I've done, the most vital is coordinating the talent of those who work for me and pointing them toward a certain goal.”

The “Disneylander” magazine (published March of 1959) first divulged these developments to Disneyland Cast Members :

“Walt Disney’s staff did some extensive research on the real Matterhorn right there in Switzerland, then, theoretically, the idea was transferred to paper - sketches, blueprints, and working drawings by Walt Disney’s WED Enterprises. That’s the way it’s usually done. But, building a mountain proved more difficult than expected, even to the Disney staff at WED. Art Director Vic Greene, found that the usual artist’s renderings and blueprints were inadequate. Sketches could only show limited views and not all of the architectural data so, a scale model of clay was made in the Studio Model Shop.”

This work was performed by “Vic Greene, and the model shop staff, Wathel Rogers, Fred Joerger and Harriet Burns… working closely with Bud Washo and his fine staff… at Disneyland. Bud’s crew and the Model Shop… [were] molding and building the ‘show aspects.’ - the life-like walls of the glacier grottos inside the mountain, and the ‘snow-capped’ peak.”

The aforementioned “scale model” was then “studied, changed, and remodeled, then another type model was built. A model of the steel structure. Step by step this model grew (and changed) constantly until it was ready for the first step of actual construction.

The actual steel structure was copied, in scale, from this model. The first basic steel work of the Matterhorn was rising in the sky to a height of a 14-story building - the tallest structure in Orange County.

This constant step-by-step growth of first model, then actual structure,… [continued] throughout the entire construction, including the final step of landscaping.”

Disneyland was 3 1/2 years old and included a number of improvements spread across its approximate 252.6 acres (with some $8,820,000 of improvements planned for both Disneyland and the Disneyland Hotel). Soon, by September 28, 1958, Disneyland, Inc. job number 4063-508 (for a new Overall Master Plot Plan of Disneyland detailing general new area development) was in progress, a financial asset valued alone at $15,625. This Master Plot Plan included Matterhorn mountain (job 4064-510; a capital job valued at $26,734) with its Matterhorn bob sled ride (job 4064-113; a capital job valued at $2,857).

To support this massive expansion, Disneyland, Inc. required a loan through Bank of America. By September of 1958, a Park-wide appraisal was conducted of all cash, accounts receivable, employee benefits, liabilities, deposits, advances, stockholder’s equity, Park assets (including land, adjoining properties, service areas, and utilities), and even those aforementioned jobs in progress. Notwithstanding the Master Plot Plan, before work began, a loan through Bank of America required an Appraiser’s Report on City Real Estate to be conducted on 1313 Harbor Boulevard. The report was conducted on December 5, 1958, by P.G. Maga, J.L. Bryant, and J.C. Biggers. The results of the appraisal found that the land was valued at $5,180,000 while the improvements were valued at $8,820,000, and a total $114, 000, 000. The report was reviewed and approved by Assistant Vice President R.A. Pifari.

Now you may have heard the old expression about “making a mountain out of a molehill.” Well that is exactly what occurred next.

Joe Fowler (Disneyland Operations Committee) oversaw the Construction & Maintenance division including Engineering, New Construction, Maintenance, and Janitorial related to the installation of the attraction.

In 1958, Disneyland Guided Tour scripts highlighted future attractions of “Lookout Mountain” this way : “Lookout Mountain will soon be converted into the Matterhorn, with a real toboggan ride and artificial snow. The Skyway will go through the mountain instead of over it, as it now does.”

Even before it’s debut, new advertisements (distributed to Disneyland guests) invited all visitors to visit “the greatest construction show on earth”! Simultaneously, flyers distributed at the Disneyland Main Gate Entrance began to advertise the $55 million 11-acre “new” addition to Walt Disney’s Disneyland. This new Disneyland development was soon to be located between Fantasyland and Tomorrowland.

Soaring skyward in spectacular style, this 1/100th scale model of Switzerland’s famed Matterhorn nears completion in Anaheim, California. Made of steel, the breathtaking “mountain” is 14 stories high (147½ feet high). The newest ride at the amusement center, the “Matterhorn” would be ready for operation in June. A bobsled would carry customers up and down the mountain.

Most of the rocks and the mountains in Disneyland are products of the Staff Shop. The rocky formation of the Matterhorn was made by the Disneyland Staff and Plaster Shop. “Staff” is a movie making expression and trade which was brought into prominence at Disneyland. Plastering, on the other hand is one of the most ancient crafts, Egyptian pyramids containing plastering which is more than four thousand years old. At Disneyland, there are “plasterers, plaster tenders, cement mason generals (not military men), cement masons, machinists, cement mason high timers, sculptors, shop hands, model makers, molders, casters, laborers, mural lathers, board lathers, and welder lathers.”

According to Long Beach Independent (January 25, 1959 : “Wood frame, lath mesh, and a two-inch layer of plaster will be applied over the steel super-structure.” In fact, enough plywood for 27 homes was utilized for the wood frame and then metal lath mesh (to hold the plaster, which was sprayed on). Guided Tour scripts of 1962 would revise this figure this way : “the Matterhorn (the Disneyland one) is made of enough lumber to build 250 three-bedroom homes.” Above, you’ll note that the finishing touches have already begun to be applied by plasterers (like Dewey Vay and Tom Emanuel). “The ‘snow-capped’ peak has been ‘sculptured’ over a metal frame and transformed into ‘rock’ with color-impregnated cement (mixing the natural color into the cement is an art in its own right). Even the ‘snow’ is cement,” according to “Disneylander” (published March of 1959). Frequently, they have had to turn to nature to find the answer for questions such as how to make natural rock. The exterior of the Matterhorn required almost two acres of metal lath . . . covered with cement from two to three inches thick.

The steel and Gunite ingredients proved successful elements, and were soon used to bring Tahitian Terrace’s Disneydendron to life. Bob Milek recalled: “When the Matterhorn was being built we were using the police channel for communications...until they told the crew to clean up their conversation or get off the air. So we used walkie-talkies!“

Attractions required illumination, and George Feldcamp and Jim Eddy worked on the lighting for the subs and the Matterhorn.

“Climb the mountain...touch the sun...you can do it...you’re the one.” So went the lyrics of "Climb the Mountain" (by Franklyn Marks). That song (first featured in William Alwyn’s musical score for Third Man on the Mountain). This was not the first time that mountain climbers appeared in a Walt Disney Production, as Mickey, Goofy, and Donald Duck ascended a mountain in Alpine Climbers (1936).

Climb the Mountain was also sang during the Matterhorn’s televised opening ceremony (Disneyland’59), while a costumed climber ascended the peak.

An American flag and Swiss flag were raised atop the Matterhorn’s peak, signaling Sierra Club Member Chuck Wilks to put a rope through the carabiner and over his shoulder. Chuck was preparing for the first official (and historic) costumed absent down the Matterhorn. Thrilled crowds watched has he belayed toward the base of the Matterhorn. On the ground, the first costumed climb was celebrated by a show of traditional Swiss Alpine Dancers followed by a traditional American Square-Dance!

Since then, Atmosphere Entertainment complimenting the theme of the area was staged on the Matterhorn to entertain Disneyland Guests on an immediate and personal level. Numerous other climbers would follow in Chuck Wilks’ footsteps, as Chuck was responsible for the placement of the pitons that secure climber’s ropes along three routes - the Italian Ridge, South Ridge, and Fuergon Ridge. However, Chuck wasn’t the very first Climber to scale the Mighty Matterhorn. It was actually Edward Kuz (of Garden Grove, California), who was a carpenter’s foreman directing the framework construction of the mountain’s upper portion. He made daily ascents up the unfinished steel framework of the mountain beginning in March of 1959.

I am reminded of Walt’s words (often quoted during ceremony): “Somehow I can’t believe there are any heights that can’t be scaled by a man who knows the secret of making dreams come true.” Many of the subsequent climbers during the 1960’s were hired by Chuck Wheelan (of Disneyland Personnel), who “went to the Sierra Club to get them.” These would assume the roles of “Hans” and “Otto,” who could “be seen climbing the icy slopes of the treacherous Matterhorn nine times a day.” [“Disneyland Holiday Talent Master Schedule,” prepared for the period of December 16, 1967 through January 1, 1968]

While the closest most individuals got toward “taking a swing at” the Matterhorn’s slopes was the 5th hole of The Magic Kingdom Golf Course (of the Disneyland Hotel Golf Centre), a typical daily schedule of “Mountain Climbers” performances looked like this :

10:30am - South Ridge

11:05am - Fuergon Ridge

11:55am - South Ridge

12:30pm - Italian Ridge

1:45pm - Fuergon Ridge

2:35pm - South Ridge

(Double Traverse) - Fuergon Ridge

4:00pm - South Ridge

(Double Traverse) - Fuergon Ridge

They also were part of the 1962-63 Winter Holiday Talent Schedule.

Pictured Above : Hans and Fritz prepare to descend the Mighty Matterhorn, (or are they ascending the perilous peak)? Photos from this shoot (shot by Disneyland Photographer Charlie Nichols) were used for publication (like the color cover of Vacationland, of Winter/Spring, 1963).

Hans (?) Contemporaneous climbers recollect an older Climbing Supervisor named Hans.

Robert “Bobby” Hight (c.1965) - This Sierra Club Member went on to pilot the Mark Twain. At that time, Mike O’ Brien of Backstage Disneyland magazine (Vol.4, No.4 ; December 1965) commented : “Marcia Henderson, of Storybook Land, would like very very much to work on the Matterhorn.” We do not know if this was written “tongue-in-cheek,” but women would begin to ascend the slopes very soon.

John Jay "Frenchy" Pelletier (1965-1966) - Walt Disney personally gave him the nickname “Frenchy” ; he had the privilege of seeing the Bell System Rocket Belt flight from the Matterhorn.

Rich Chambers (1966 -1968)

John Atherton (1966 - ) - met true-life alpinists Sir Edmond and Lady Hillary

November 26, 1972 through May 26, 1973, Hans, Otto, Fritz (Mountain Climbers) was among the Atmosphere Talent and Shows.

Frank Nosalek

Cindy Brack McGrew (late 1970s) - She was “very close to” Snow White, before becoming Disneyland’s first female Matterhorn Climber! A nod to this is subtly mentioned in the official “Disney News” magazine (of Spring, 1974). In response to an inquiry by Cary Pereira of Fremont, California, the Editor writes : “Hans, Otto, and Gretchen are expert rock climbers who tackle the 147-foot-high Matterhorn every day throughout the summer season. As there are no preset handholds or footholds, the climbers consider Disneyland’s Matterhorn a daily challenge.”

Jeff Anderson (?) - Later, trained climbers for Disneyland’s 30th Anniversary.

***SHOW DISCONTINUED in 1979***

Numerous new Matterhorn Mountain Climbers scaled the slopes of the mighty peak during Disneyland’s anniversaries (as during the years 1985 - 1986)! Issues of Disneyland LINE (as Vol.19, No.20 ; published May 14, 1987) ran “Attention : Climbers” advertisements reading : “The Character/Parade Department is looking for individuals to climb the Matterhorn. Applicants must be at least 18 years of age and have at least two years of climbing experience. If you know someone who meets the above requirements and is interested in this position, please have them submit a resume to : Tim Runco (Marketing/Entertainment Division)…The resume should include areas climbed, routes climbed, and routes they have led.”

Paul Petersen (1985) - former Climber who climbed, and helped ready the Matterhorn for Disneyland’s 30th Anniversary)

Art Grimes (1985) - former Climber who climbed, and helped ready the Matterhorn for Disneyland’s 30th Anniversary)

Tim Runco (1985) - Character Parades Department Manager, who climbed and readied the Matterhorn for Disneyland’s 30th Anniversary. Repairs were noted, and the mountain was “repossessed from the pigeons”.

Peter Morgan (c. 1985) - Climbed for a Special Show in celebration of Disnyland’s 30th anniversary.

Debbiy Gilchrist (c. 1985) - Climber Lead for a Special Show in celebration of Disnyland’s 30th anniversary.

Keith Wing (c. 1985) - This Main Street Culinary Host turns Climber, and climbed for a Special Show in celebration of Disnyland’s 30th anniversary.

Michael Egan (1985) - A new Climber, who climbed for the summer season of a Special Show in celebration of Disnyland’s 30th anniversary.

Jeff Harris (1985) - A new Climber, who climbed for the summer season of a Special Show in celebration of Disnyland’s 30th anniversary.

David Jarvis (1985) - A new Climber, who climbed for the summer season of a Special Show in celebration of Disnyland’s 30th anniversary.

Steve Sosa (1985) - A new Climber, who climbed for the summer season of a Special Show in celebration of Disnyland’s 30th anniversary.

John (?) (1987) - Multiple climbers of this era recollect a climber named John. Sadly, none of them can recollect John’s last name.

Marc Haxton (1995-1997) - He was “close to Mickey Mouse” during one of his three years of climbing the Matterhorn!

During this era of Disneyland’s 40th (c. 1995-1996), Disneyland Characters (like Mickey Mouse and Goofy) made appearances from the top of the Matterhorn, Indiana Jones rappelled from the Matterhorn to Sleeping Beauty Castle, and Randy Travis sang the “Mickey Mouse Club March” from the top of the Matterhorn (while a banner reading “Disneyland Happy 40th Birthday” was unfurled)!

In 2001, the Matterhorn Experience was auctioned off at the 2001 Official Disneyana Convention at Disneyland Resort. The experience offered a "climb" with the Disneyland Resort photographer to learn the backstage secrets of the Matterhorn and receive a breathtaking view of Disneyland on the morning of Saturday, September 8, 2001. The experience sold for $13,000.

“I had just come from Canada in 1960, and gone from country living to city living. In 1960, Dad got a new job and took the family to Disneyland. I was 15 the first time I went. At that time they had Tom Sawyer’s Island and I enjoyed that, the Indian War Canoes and the Mule Train. Mom and Dad loved the Golden Horseshoe Saloon. We had ice cream, pop corn, apple candy, and that sort of stuff. I remember the fantasy of it all, and the characters. That was my first experience with Disneyland.

One of my teachers worked for Disneyland and mentioned that Disneyland was hiring. Steve (a friend of mine) said “Do you want to go work for Disneyland?” We went down and applied. Come middle of May of 1965 he got a job right away on the Autopia motor cars, the Monorail, and eventually the [Santa Fe &] Disneyland Railroad trains. I never got the call and went to work with my dad in the oil fields.

It was the middle of June and I got the call. They asked if I worked with animals and mules, and i mentioned how I lived around animals in Canada. They said we have an opening on the Mule Train around $1.75 an hour. In 1965 that was a lot of money. I went to work for the Mule Train, and the next thing I knew I had my own train. I would load the kids, get the animals and feed them a little, give them a break, get back in line, and do it all again.

Around July they had an opening in the talent division of the park. We had just climbed Mount Whitney (that was a challenge), and Big Bear. They told me, “Put in your name next to the division where you are working, near the time clock.” The next day there was a note stashed by my name near the time clock. The note said to ‘not go to your work station’ and ‘see Scott’.

He [Scott] took me to a side door in the Matterhorn Mountain. The inside was nothing but “2 by 4s”. It looked like an old house under construction. Fred was a lead at the time, and he asked if I knew any knots. I did about six knots for Scott and Fred, and they asked “Are you familiar with belaying?” I told them that I wasn’t an expert.

Fred instructed me to “put on a harness and we’ll go outside and try some things”. There was no worry, I belayed and got down there no problem. After I got back up there, Fred says “You’re hired. Today will be your last day in your old station.”

According to “THE DISNEY THEME SHOW - an introduction to the art of Disney outdoor entertainment”: “Important are the sounds which permeate the scene, for without them, the theme show is a silent movie . . . but with them it is a symphony of music, effects, and natural sounds that the finest stereo system in the world can't duplicate. These sights and sounds are provided not only by imagineered attractions and shows, but also through the multi-talented efforts of live entertainers . . . in special musical groups . . . in parades and pageants . . . providing an everchanging backdrop to virtually every area in the theme show.”

Bernie the Yodeler would interact with climbers on the summit.

Former Matterhorn Climber Geoffrey remembers, “Bernie shared the Break Room with us. He usually played the accordion, but he knew how to yodel, and he played the trumpet (which meant that he knew how to play the Alp Horn). He played it beautifully.” The Alp Horn may sound beautiful, but it‘s a heavy instrument, and challenging to position from some Matterhorn locations.

Alan remembers one time that Bernie played the Alp Horn during their ascent. “The Dressing Room is under Coke Terrace, and just outside the Dressing Room to the right were the stairs that went up to the stage that came out of the ground to Coke Terrace. To the left was a showroom (with lots of stuff stored in there). Jeff and I were wandering around in there one day, and we found the Alp Horn. So we got it to Bernie, and we talked him into going up on the mountain with us.

So he went up, just to the very first stage (where you walk out onto the mountain). We set him up on a platform out there - the biggest platform that there was, and he played the Alp Horn. People started to come. That was the biggest crowd we ever had!

He stood there the whole time we climbed up. Then he played descending notes as we came down. Then we rappelled back down, and went in. He [Bernie] said, ‘I’m never doing that again’.”

Brian Buchiarelli began climbing Disneyland’s Matterhorn for four years starting in 1969 shares a few thoughts on his experience :

SO, HOW DID YOU BECOME A MATTERHORN CLIMBER?

“My brother Geoff worked at the Matterhorn and Disneyland before I did. He graduated from UCLA, he was in the ROTC program, went in the navy, and got married all at the same time. So (nepotism at work), he wanted to know if I wanted the job, and I said, ‘sure’. I went, and applied, and got hired, and I was there for four years!

HOW MANY CLIMBERS WERE THERE AT ONE TIME?

“There were always four climbers (one guy had the day off, while the other three climbed).”

WERE THERE ANY ADDED SHOW ELEMENTS THAT ENHANCED THE MATTERHORN CLIMBING EXPERIENCE?

“When I worked there, there was Fred the Yodeler. He was Swiss, and he had his authentic ‘getup’, and he played the accordion. I would do a little bit of yodeling, and he and I would do a shtick : he would yodel up to me, and I would yodel down to him.

If you rappelled, you could come down in about three or four jumps. If two of you rappel at the same, you could criss-cross across each other. Sometimes we would fall on purpose. We would be on the overhang, give ourselves some slack, and scream ‘Falling’. You’ve got to put on a show.”

WHAT’S THE TALLEST MOUNTAIN YOU’VE EVER VISITED?

“I’ve seen the real Mount Everest, when I went to Nepal. I don’t know if you’re familiar with Douglas Adams’ The Restaurant at the End of Universe. From Kathmandu, you can go and stay in a hotel that has a sign reading ‘The Restaurant at the End of Universe’ The next morning, they wake you up, so that you can see the sunrise from Mount Everest - it’s really, really beautiful!”

NOW THAT YOU’VE VISITED THE TRUE-LIFE MATTERHORN IN SWITZERLAND, AND YOU’VE ASCENDED DISNEYLAND’S OWN “PERILOUS PEAK” - WHAT’S NEXT?

“That’s it. [chuckles] After climbing the Matterhorn at Disneyland, it doesn’t get much better than being at the real Matterhorn! For my 60th birthday, Geoff and my little brother Phil treated me to trip to Walt Disney World in Florida. We went to all the different lands, including Expedition Everest in Walt Disney’s Animal Kingdom. It’s so magnificent!

HOW WOULD YOU RATE YOUR ENTIRE EMPLOYMENT EXPERIENCE?

“To get paid for your sport - it doesn’t get much better than that. It was probably the best job I ever had!”

Safety is a major concern of Engineering.

During each day, Disneyland Park Operations M-42 Machinists would, at least once, check all attractions in Fantasyland and discuss with each Attraction Lead and problems, defects, or any other feedback regarding the department. M-42 Machinists would also respond to all downs and delayed openings in the Fantasyland area whether or not it was mechanical. Upon arriving at an attraction, they would determine whether what the failure was. M-42 would determine which crafts were needed, determine an estimated time of repair, notify M-1 and assist with crafts when necessary.

Every year the Matterhorn Rehab Crew would make a complete test and inspection of all structural parts of Disneyland. And since Guests would look to Disneyland for their safety the department team was continuously designing new guest and personnel safety devices.

The Disneyland welding department maintained the Matterhorn track. This, like all other Disneyland metal structures, is regularly X-rayed to determine its strength. This type of job is major, planned rehabilitation, as opposed to a hurry-up repair job on a dancing doll in Small World.

Disneyland Building and Grounds Department would regularly clean the snow on top of the Matterhorn.

Paint was also important. The “Master Color Book” is the Bible for color selection at Disneyland, maintaining a catalogue of 4,000 shades of color. “Participant Sponsorship”

Our story begins in 1954, when Walt was searching for participants to lease shop and restaurant spaces at Disneyland, and help generate the necessary capital to fund construction of Disneyland. In a synergistic relationship, the companies (in turn) could sell their products and advertise their corporate names in the Park. Disneyland Participant Corporate Sponsors were carefully selected. High quality, long term corporate sponsors would provide incremental income that enabled Disneyland to enhance its show and attractions, offset some operating expenses, and capitalize on marketing opportunities.

Several of these turn-of-the-century pioneers, “reliable old firms” sponsored the “abundance of restaurants devoted to pleasing all tastes and all budgets,” according to “The Story of Disneyland,” published 1955. Ultimately, Maxwell Coffee House Division of General Foods became one of those forty-seven lessees to sign a contract with Walt Disney Productions (regarding creating happiness at Walt Disney’s Disneyland)!

It was estimated that the table service facility would have the capacity to serve about 400 guests per hour. Despite the fact that Maxwell Coffee House Restaurant did not open in July of 1955, it became reckoned among Disneyland’s twenty eating facilities which were predicted to contribute to accommodating “15,000 persons daily, hitting a peak of 60,000 o holidays and week-ends…” and one of “twenty restaurants and snack bars, capable of saving 8,000 hourly,” at least according to “Building A Dream” (prepared by the Disneyland, Inc. Public Relations Department). Years later in 1958, Bank of America appraisers figured of the total income received from leases, 16.02% was derived from the selling of advertising rights and 40.12% from the leasing of space to concerns whose main reason for occupancy is for advertising purposes. The remaining 43.86% of the lease income was derived from stores that sell various products and food. It is this income that supported the construction and growth of Disneyland. Clearly, these participant corporate sponsors were not here to make money, but to create happiness!

“Design”

According to “THE DISNEY THEME SHOW - an introduction to the art of Disney outdoor entertainment: Volume II”: Of all the guests’ senses that come into play at Disneyland, the most difficult response to predict was taste. If 70,000 guests were to arrive on a single day, there would probably be 70,000 different ideas about food. Generally speaking, Disneyland food locations fall into three categories - sit-down restaurant service, “buffeteria,” and fast-food categories. The most extensive theming has always been found in the sit-down restaurant locations but all locations were housed in authentically motified facilities.

As Walt described to Bob Thomas (of Associated Press), “some industries will have exhibits, but all of them must be in keeping with the era.” Soon (c. 1954-1955), Sam McKim (with audiences in mind) and possibly other contributing artists were creating designs for the Maxwell Coffee House Restaurant Show Building Facade. This building would camouflage a construction wall.

Early thumbnail sketches and other concept artwork of Disneyland seemed to be unencumbered by restrictions of budget, schedule or the laws of nature and physics. Though guided by Walt, his artists appeared to engage in “free-thinking,” as if implementing the modern “Blue Sky” Imagineering process. Like some advanced “High Concept,” final designs were quickly generated and approved.

Next, architectural drawings helped define all designs, production and construction strategies, costs, schedule, and resource requirements. “Disneyland is unique in that some of the world's foremost creative artists and architects control all design at Disneyland.“ Models explored the various dimensional relationships, site-lines, flow patterns, ergonomics, and visual appeal to convey the desired creative intent.

“Construction”

“When the giant earth-moving undertaking was completed, the building crews took over. Soon, the rat-tat-tat of riveters was shattering the air, and sparks were flying from welders’ torches as the steel frameworks, capable of withstanding the ravages of time and the elements rose above the newly formed ground. While carpenters hammered and masons laid row upon row of brick and stone and mortar, the permanent buildings began to take shape and form,” according to “The Disneyland Story” published 1955. One of the first buildings to be constructed was the Main Street Opera House, which was used as the Mill. Here, the woodwork of Disneyland was generated - from the functional to the aesthetic! Approximately three and one-half million board feet of lumber went into the Park’s construction. Much of the wood was processed here by McNeil Construction (which formerly constructed Walt Disney Studio sound stages in 1947 and 1953), and under the direction of George Mills Sr. (the Prime General Contractor and Mill Foreman).

Then, under the direction of Joe Fowler (Construction Supervisor), as well as Charles Alexander and Ray Conway (Construction Field Supervisors), the lumber was soon fashioned into the framing belonging to the very first buildings constructed at Disneyland - primarily the Main Street Complexes (on each side of the street).

In constructing each building, a concrete foundation and slab floors were prepared, followed by wood frame construction (while store units would have a combination wood and rigid steel frame). ”The first fabricated steel for the Main Street buildings arrived November 8 and was erected,” according to the narrator of “Disneyland - The Park,” a Disneyland anthology television series excerpt, first aired 1957 and Disneyland LINE (November 22, 1979). The roof covering was a variable, dependent on the architectural design.

As of June 2, 1955, C.V. Wood Jr. sent an Inter-Office Memorandum to Walt Disney regarding the best estimates that could be obtained at the time regarding the completion status of individual sections of the Park and Opening Day. C.V. wrote: “Building #612 - Maxwell House. Will not be completed. We will have to dress. Electric Signs: All are in work - with the exception of the shoe store and the Bank of America, all will be completed.“

The building (as each on Main Street U.S.A.) possessed complete fire sprinkling systems. By June 30, 1955, related Disneyland Site Work Fire Protection Utilities Plot Plans were prepared for Disneyland Inc., by J.E. Thomasson of WED Enterprises Inc.

All fixtures were placed in their correct motif and many light fixtures of Disneyland were authentic antiques. The Disneyland News added: “From its wrought iron and old stonework exterior to the patio-type serving area, the Maxwell House represents all that was fine and gracious in turn-of-the-century life in the New Orleans section of the Old South. The wrought iron work and staff work was also performed right on the jobsite by Lawrence G. and Bruce McNeil’s forces.

“HOWDY FOLKS! Welcome to the little mining town of Rainbow Ridge - the gateway to Nature’s Wonderland.” When Disneyland first opened there were only a few ways to explore this portion of Frontierland - all of them by horse or mule. There were Stagecoaches, Conestoga Wagons, Yellowstone Coaches, and mule trains which traversed seven acres of Disneyland to bring it all to life.

“New Pages of the Disneyland Story”

Now, on the eve of Disneyland’s first day of operation, Walt had promised that “Disneyland will never be completed. It will continue to grow, to add new things, as long as there is imagination left in the world.” So it must have seemed strange to some when a year later (during 1956), “a few of Disneyland’s fabulous rides closed temporarily, [when] construction operations in Frontierland… made it necessary to shut down the three ‘Painted Desert’ rides - the Stage Coach, the Mule Pack Train and the Conestoga wagon,” according to “The Disneyland News” (Extra Edition). Only a few days prior, at a meeting of the Disneyland Merchant's Association (held January 25, 1956), a momentous announcement was made: “All horsedrawn vehicles in the Frontierland area will be shutdown for approximately two months, during the redesign and reconstruction of this area. This will be a whole new development to increase ride capacity. We are building a mountain to be called Rainbow Mountain. This will be seen from the River and the Mark Twain. The existing corral and Black smith Show will be the entrance to a new ‘Mine Train’ ride. This will be an old fashioned Mining Train with 6 open cars. The engine will look like a real engine. The ride will go through a canyon out into the desert; then into a Rainbow Mountain where you tunnell with stalagmites and stalactities and three different water falls of different colors, joining in the river. This ride will take about 6 minutes. One of the most interesting rides we have in the park is the True Life Boat Ride. Me hope to make the ‘Mine Ride’ an equal to that one.”

Though Walt set the “Painted Desert” budget at $400,000, nearly $500,000 of improvements (of a total $1.5 million total Park investments for 1956) brought major developments and “reconditioning” to the Painted Desert area of Frontierland! A new town sprang up in the hills overlooking Frontierland, newly rails were laid, and the opportunity arose to head past rushing rivers and into the uncharted caverns and caves of the Painted Desert! “Towering above the scene, Rainbow Mountain provides a snow-capped background for all this action,” according to the “Disneyland 1st Anniversary Souvenir Pictorial,” published 1956.

As some of these new Frontierland attractions appeared on page 5 of The Disneyland News (published June of 1956), the Rainbow Caverns Mine Train began to prove the truth of Walt Disney’s promise of an ever-expanding Disneyland! Similar to how Walt Disney’s True Life Adventure series spawned True Life Adventureland, Nature’s Wonderland (and its refurbishment) were directly influenced by films released from 1950 to 1954. But while those films were “two-dimensional in scope, the Theme Park surrounds the guests with the story and impacts all of their senses”, according to “Disney By Design” Tour scripts. Artists like set designer Wilson “Bill” Martin (who had left 20th Century Fox, to work on Walt Disney Productions’ Disneyland project) was influential in the design of Nature’s Wonderland, his talents as art director applied to the attraction.

Though total investment for Disneyland had now reached $18,500,000, the rich story of the Mine Train was among the attractions that were projected to add a 40% ride capacity to the Park!

Today, our story begins at a junction in the small mining town of Rainbow Ridge. Instead of saddling up atop a dusty pack mule, we’ll load into a mine train gondola for what would typically be a seven minute excursion, en route to a “wondrous” destination tucked deep in the earth! A place where (according to Holiday magazine, published Summer, 1958), “seven multicolored waterfalls cascade and stalactites and stalagmites form beautiful patterns.” However, today we won’t look at our watches, or worry about the uniform “trip time.” We won’t heavily rely on the pre-recorded voice-over narration of Dallas McKinnon, or the script. Instead, I’ll be providing a custom spiel along our journey, which will be of an undetermined time length.

Our “tickets for today’s adventure”, and a rare view of the magnificent Rainbow Caverns tickets (pictured above), come courtesy of collector and historian James Keeline. Further, James is “just the ticket” when it comes to the facts about these rare Rainbow Mountain attraction admission tickets!

What were the earliest Disneyland tickets like?

“In the first few years of Disneyland the tickets sold inside the park were often for specific attractions. There were also tickets sold, perhaps at a later date, with A-B-C-D-E.”

“We can fine tune it by noticing the adult price…on the ticket…(50¢). The price stayed the same for a few years but the lettered individual tickets started to appear in this era too.”

“The region was initially called the ‘Painted Desert’ [in 1955]. It was redeveloped to add the Mine Train and the name became the ‘Rainbow Desert.’ The desert portion was called the ‘Living Desert’ for the Nature's Wonderland era.”

Our Rainbow Caverns tickets will be taken by the Ticket Receptionist, on the Rainbow Ridge Boarding Platform, before embarking on our journey.
